Kuri-Kinton (Updated — Using Candied Chestnuts in Syrup)

Ingredients (Serves 2)

Sweet Potato Base
	•	250 g (8.8 oz) Japanese sweet potato (satsumaimo), peeled
	•	10 g (0.35 oz) unsalted butter

Sweetening & Balance
	•	15–20 g (1–1½ tbsp) granulated sugar, to taste
	•	1 g (scant ¼ tsp) salt

Chestnut Finish
	•	60 g (2.1 oz) candied chestnuts in syrup, drained
	•	0–10 g (0–2 tsp) chestnut syrup, optional (for texture/gloss only)

⸻

Method
	1.	Prep Sweet Potato
Slice into 2 cm rounds. Soak in cold water 10 minutes to remove surface starch; drain well.
	2.	Steam
Steam until a skewer passes through with gentle resistance, about 15 minutes.
	3.	Season & Mash
While hot, sprinkle with salt and mash coarsely to distribute seasoning evenly.
	4.	Brown Butter
Melt butter in a saucepan over medium heat until lightly browned and nutty. Immediately add mashed sweet potato.
	5.	Refine Texture
Mash and stir continuously until completely smooth and uniform, avoiding scorching.
	6.	Prepare Chestnuts
Finely chop the drained candied chestnuts, then mash or pass through a sieve until smooth.
	7.	Sweeten & Finish
Add sugar gradually to the sweet potato base, mixing well. Fold in the chestnut purée. Cook on low heat 2–3 minutes until silky and glossy. Add reserved chestnut syrup sparingly only if needed for looseness or sheen.
	8.	Chill
Transfer to a shallow container, smooth the surface, cover directly, and chill at least 30 minutes before serving.

⸻

Optional Refinements
	•	Substitute wasanbon sugar for a finer sweetness
	•	For ultra-smooth ceremonial texture, pass the finished mixture through a fine sieve
	•	Pipe into portions and top with a halved candied chestnut lightly glazed with syrup